{"topicId":"positive-definite-matrices-markov","mcqs":[{"id":"mcq-1","question":"What is the correct definition of a positive definite matrix?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"A matrix is positive definite if all its eigenvalues are positive"},{"key":"B","text":"A symmetric matrix A is positive definite if x^TAx > 0 for all non-zero vectors x"},{"key":"C","text":"A matrix is positive definite if all its entries are positive"},{"key":"D","text":"A matrix is positive definite if its determinant is positive"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"The rigorous definition requires x^TAx > 0 for ALL non-zero vectors x, not just positive eigenvalues.","difficulty":"easy"},{"id":"mcq-2","question":"Which of the following is a property of a symmetric positive definite matrix?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"All its eigenvalues are negative"},{"key":"B","text":"It can be factored as A = LL^T where L is lower triangular with positive diagonal entries (Cholesky decomposition)"},{"key":"C","text":"Its determinant is always zero"},{"key":"D","text":"It is always singular"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"A symmetric positive definite matrix can always be decomposed as A = LL^T via Cholesky decomposition.","difficulty":"easy"},{"id":"mcq-3","question":"In the context of Markov chains, a transition matrix P is stochastic if:","options":[{"key":"A","text":"All entries are positive and P = P^T"},{"key":"B","text":"Each row sums to 1 and all entries are non-negative"},{"key":"C","text":"P has only positive eigenvalues and is symmetric"},{"key":"D","text":"P is positive definite and has determinant 1"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"A stochastic matrix for Markov chains has non-negative entries with each row summing to 1.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-4","question":"For a symmetric matrix, which condition is NOT equivalent to positive definiteness?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"All eigenvalues are positive"},{"key":"B","text":"All leading principal minors are positive (Sylvester's criterion)"},{"key":"C","text":"x^TAx > 0 for all non-zero x"},{"key":"D","text":"The matrix can be written as BB^T for some matrix B"}],"correctAnswer":"D","explanation":"A symmetric matrix is positive definite iff A = BB^T where B is nonsingular, not just any B.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-5","question":"What is the relationship between positive definiteness and the convergence of Markov chains?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"All transition matrices of Markov chains must be positive definite"},{"key":"B","text":"If a stochastic matrix has eigenvalue 1 with multiplicity 1 and all other eigenvalues have absolute value less than 1, the Markov chain converges to a stationary distribution"},{"key":"C","text":"Positive definite matrices cannot be used in Markov chain analysis"},{"key":"D","text":"The transition matrix must be symmetric positive definite for convergence"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"Convergence in Markov chains depends on the spectral gap—eigenvalue 1 must be simple and other eigenvalues must satisfy |λ| < 1.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-6","question":"Which of the following matrices is positive definite?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"[[2, -1], [-1, 2]]"},{"key":"B","text "[[1, 2], [2, 1]]"},{"key":"C","text "[[0, 1], [1, 0]]"},{"key":"D","text "[[-1, 0], [0, -1]]"}],"correctAnswer":"A","explanation":"The matrix [[2,-1],[-1,2]] has eigenvalues 1 and 3 (both positive), so it is symmetric positive definite.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-7","question":"Consider a covariance matrix of a random vector in a Markov random field. Which property must it satisfy?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"It must be a stochastic matrix"},{"key":"B","text":"It must be positive definite to represent valid variances and covariances"},{"key":"C","text":"It must have all off-diagonal entries negative"},{"key":"D","text":"It must be skew-symmetric"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"Covariance matrices must be positive definite (or positive semi-definite) to ensure valid probability distributions.","difficulty":"hard"},{"id":"mcq-8","question":"For a Markov chain with transition matrix P, the matrix Q = I - P + π1^T (where π is the stationary distribution) is often used in analysis. This matrix Q is:","options":[{"key":"A","text":"Always singular"},{"key":"B","text":"Always positive definite if the chain is irreducible and aperiodic"},{"key":"C","text":"Always negative definite"},{"key":"D","text":"Always a stochastic matrix"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"For an irreducible aperiodic Markov chain, this centered matrix is positive definite due to the spectral properties ensuring convergence.","difficulty":"hard"}]}